Q: How can we classify problems based on how difficult (hard) they are to solve?
A: We use several different complexity classes to classify a problem based on how difficult it is to solve.

  P - (Polynomial time) Deterministic problems that are solvable in polynomial time. These are problems that computers 
      can solve efficiently. Problems within this class live within O(n), O(nlogn), O(n^2), and O(n^3)

  NP - (Non-deterministic polynomial time) If someone hands you a solution, you can verify it quickly. This doesn't
       mean finding the solution would be quick also, might actually be very slow. NP includes all problmes in P,
       plus harder problems. Decision problems (deciding whether a proposed solution is true or false)
       A proposed solution can be verified (yes/no) in polynomial time.

  NP-Complete - (NPC) These are the hardest problems in NP. Every NP problem can be reduced to these in polynomial
                time. If you solve one NP-Complete problem efficiently, you solve all fo NP.
                A Polynomial-time algorithm for any NPC problem would imply P = NP

                ** No polynomial-time algorithm has ever been found for any NP-Complete problem. BUT, none has
                   been proven proven impossible either! Exactly the debate whether P=NP

  NP-Hard - At least as hard as the hardest problems in NP, but not necessarily in NP themselves

  (P = NP means: every problem whose solution can be verified quickly, can also be solved quickly)

